column5:
Laryngeal colouring

Likely the earliest traditionally dateable sound change in Carite, and in Indo-European in general, is laryngeal colouring. As its traces can be seen even across Anatolian, it is likely that an allophonic process of vowel colouring next to the traditionally posited laryngeals *h₂ *h₃ predates the Anatolian split. This had little effect on the morphology of Indo-European early on, and only later did it influence its grammatical ablaut. A generalised overview of the process:|-|As in other Indo-European languages, the effects of laryngeal colouring are recoverable only for the vowel *e, and not any other vowel; whether this is due to its effect only on this vowel, or that the effects of colouring on other vowels were lost, is indeterminable. The often reported colouring of *o next to *h₂ in Latin and Greek is convincingly refuted by §h2oproblem§.

Due to how widespread this change was, examples in other branches are plentiful. Compare the following:

  • pie@bʰréh₂tēr|bʰréh₂tēr > °FRATERBROTHER°, pclt@brātīr|brātīr, grc@φρᾱ́τηρ|φρᾱ́τηρ=phrā́tēr, lat@frāter|frāter, pgmc@brōþēr|brōþēr (through *brāþēr)
  • pie@h₂érh₃trom|h₂érh₃trom > °PLOUGHARD°, pclt@aratrom|aratrom, grc@ἄροτρον|ἄροτρον=árotron, lat@arātrum|arātrum, pgmc@arþraz|arþraz
  • pie@déh₃nom|déh₃nom > °GIFTDONUM° (through *dṓnom), pclt@dānus|dānus (through *dōnus), lat@dōnum|dōnum; pie@déh₃rom|déh₃rom > grc@δῶρον|δῶρον=dôron; pie@bʰleh₃tís|bʰleh₃tís > pgmc@blōdiz|blōdiz
  • pie@h₃éwis|h₃éwis > °OWISSHEEP°, pclt@owis|owis, grc@ὄϊς|ὄϊς=óïs, lat@ovis|ovis, pgmc@awiz|awiz (through *owiz)

The vocalism in °GIFTDONUM° is the result of a later raising of stressed *ō. Note that the vocalism in pgmc@brōþēr reflects a later merger of *ā into *ō and the vocalism in pgmc@awiz reflects a later merger of *o into *a.
column10:
Cluster assimilation

Voicing assimilation in obstruent clusters is another extremely early Indo-European phenomenon. It predates all the other recoverable processes, and its age relative to laryngeal colouring cannot be determined. The process dictates the spread of voicing from the final element in a cluster regressively:
column12: This change also operated when the cluster included aspirates: they can be assumed to also be voiced, or breathily/partially voiced, to begin with. All aspirates in such clusters presumably become voiceless aspirates, but their result cannot be shown to be different from regular voiced obstruents: presumably, this aspiration is lost early enough internally to merge their outcome with that of regular tenues, and not (the somewhat later) voiceless aspirates.
column13: A somewhat later process, Siebs' Law, changed this system after the rise and proliferation of prefixed s-mobile. Word-initial clusters with |*sB *sBʰ|, formed morphologically, would devoice, possibly giving rise to a new set of voiceless aspirates, in addition to adding to a growing number of voiceless tenues:|-|It is not clear if the voiceless aspirates remained phonemic for long - in any case, in Carite, they behave identically to the regular voiceless tenues and presumably merged shortly after if they ever were distinct in the first place.
column14:
Dental degemination

As part of the degemination of dentals, the first dental (i.e. alveolar plosive) was affricated, and then the resulting cluster was simplified:|-|This process probably only happened only at morpheme boundaries: the pie@átta was preserved seemingly unaltered. It is possible that the word had some other process at play, or that it was a babbled word or a loan common to Indo-European; regardless, the process continued to be a productive morphophonological alternation.

This development mirrors the degemination in Greek:

  • pie@bʰéydʰtis|bʰéydʰtis > °BHIDHTIS°, grc@πίστις|πίστις=pístis

Compare this to Italic, Celtic and Germanic, where the degemination of dentals resulted in *ss:

  • pie@sedtós|sedtós > pgmc@sessaz|sessaz, lat@sessus|sessus
  • pie@medtós|medtós > pclt@messos|messos

It is likely the change was not complete yet in Celtic in Proto-Celtic times, as we find an intermediate stage in Gaulish. This reinforces the interpretation that this degemination is an independent development in the different branches.
column15:
Thorn clusters

The first was the dissolution of thorn clusters which sets the late Common Indo-European group, together with Carite, apart from earlier Indo-European. In Carite, the thorn clusters underwent metathesis:|-|The metathesis of thorn clusters is a trait shared with Celtic and Greek as demonstrated below:

  • pie@dʰǵʰési|dʰǵʰési > °YESTERDAYWORD° (through *gdesi), pclt@gdesi|gdesi, grc@χθές|χθές=khthés

The assibilation of the dental in °YESTERDAYWORD° will be discussed later. In the other western branches, the clusters were simply reduced. Examples include:

  • pie@dʰǵʰemelos|dʰǵʰemelos > lat@humilis|humilis; compare to °LOWWW° and grc@χθαμαλός|χθαμαλός=khthamalós
  • pie@dʰǵʰésros|dʰǵʰésros > pgmc@gestraz|gestraz
column17:
Osthoff's Law

Another early process in Carite history, shared with Italo-Celtic, Greek and probably Germanic, is Osthoff's Law, which dictates the shortening of sequences of long vowels followed by a resonant and another, indeterminate consonant:|-|Osthoff's Law continued to be productive until after the loss of laryngeals in all the branches, but acted as a surface filter in Carite for a particularly long time, continuing to affect later loans and formations all the way until the loss of vowel length that occured in the medieval ages. The examples below illustrate how it also divides western Indo-European from eastern languages such as Sanskrit:

  • pie@tpḗrsneh₂|tpḗrsneh₂ > °HEEL1°, grc@πτέρνη|πτέρνη=ptérnē, lat@perna|perna, pgmc@fersnō|fersnō; compare to san@पार्ष्णि=pā́rṣṇi

The continuous application of Osthoff's Law as a surface filter will continue to be pointed out in the subsequent changes.
column18:
Saussure Effect

The Saussure Effect dictated a loss of laryngeals between a resonant and a consonant, provided that the resonant was preceded by *o. While it is unclear if this effect already affected Proto-Indo-European proper or if it's a later development, it is nonetheless shared by many branches, Carite included:|-|In recent years, the legitimacy of the Saussure effect has been challenged. §greeksaussureeffect§ and §saussurepronk§ found that many of the evidence was flawed, instead proposing a new simplification of *VLHNV to *VLNV for Greek. This newly proposed revision of the Saussure Effect would be equally compatible with Carite due to the lack of interconsonantal laryngeal vocalisation if either is a semivowel (further discussed below). However, this criticism has also been met with counterarguments, primarily by §byrdsaussure§. Either way, both theories account for the Carite reflexes.
column19:
Centumisation

Centumisation in Carite took place somewhat late, and only after the coalescence of a sequence of a back velar followed by *w into a single labiovelar consonant:|-|It is worth noting that Greek, in order to preserve the length caused by the original cluster, rendered them as geminates instead.
column22:
The typical actual centumisation involved the unconditional merger of the palatovelars into regular velars as follows:|-|This reduced the triple-contrast velar series to one that only contrasted plain and labialised. Centumisation is shared with the other western languages:

  • pie@swéḱuros|swéḱuros > °SEKURUSFATHER°, pclt@swekrVnos|swekrVnos, grc@ἑκυρός|ἑκυρός=hekurós, lat@socer|socer, pgmc@swehrô|swehrô (through *swekrô)
  • pie@ǵénus|ǵénus > °GENWII°, pclt@genus|genus, grc@γένυς|γένυς=génus, lat@gena, pgmc@kinnuz|kinnuz (through *ginnuz)
  • pie@ǵʰéyōm|ǵʰéyōm > °WINTER°, pclt@gyemos|gyemos (through *gʰyemos), grc@χεῖμα|χεῖμα=kheîma, lat@hiems|hiems (through *gʰiems), pgmc@gōīn-|gōīn- (through *gʰōīn-)

Carite is peculiar in that the late centumisation, which only occurred after the coalescence of a sequence of a plain velar and *w, allows for an original contrast that is not found in the other western languages as they also merged palatovelars followed by *w with the labiovelars. For example, compare how Carite, unlike its sister centum branches, retains a sequence of a palatovelar and *w as a cluster as opposed original labiovelars and the sequence of a plain velar and *w which later shifted to fricatives as seen in the examples above - this will be discussed in greater detail later:

  • pie@h₁éḱwos|h₁éḱwos > °EKWOS°, not **εφος (**efos); compare to pclt@ekʷos|ekʷos, grc@ἵππος|ἵππος=hippos (through *íkkʷos), lat@equus|equus, pgmc@ehwaz|ehwaz (through *ekwaz)
  • pie@dn̥ǵʰwéh₂s|dn̥ǵʰwéh₂s > °DAGWAA°, not **διμθᾱ (**dimvā); compare to pclt@tangʷāts|tangʷāts (through *tangʷʰāts), lat@lingua|lingua (through *lingʷʰā), pgmc@tungǭ|tungǭ (through *tungʰwǭ)

Original *ǵw clusters are not included in the examples above as none such cluster was continued into Carite; however, we can safely assume that it would probably have had the same fate. It is worth noting that in Germanic, the fact labiovelars are written as *Cw rather than *Cʷ is purely an orthographical convention and does not mean they are clusters. The loss of the labialisation in pgmc@tungǭ is a result of delabialisation after *un.
column25: In at least one word, we find dissimilation of two labiovelars in the onset of adjacent syllables:|-|It is unknown if this change was regular or if it only affected this word in particular. No other occurences of this environment can be found, so no counterarguments can be put forward.
column26:
Laryngeal and syllabic sonorant development

Around the same time, the first loss of laryngeals occurred:|-|It is worth noting that when this sonorant was followed by another consonant, the newly lengthened vowel was subsequently shortened again through Osthoff's Law.
column27: Syllabic sonorants and laryngeals adjacent to them interacted in many branches, Carite included. Similar to Celtic, Greek and Latin, Carite inserted a prop vowel between any syllabic sonorant and a laryngeal, moving the syllabicity from the sonorant to this new prop vowel:
column33: Next, an epenthetic vowel was inserted to take up the syllabicity of any remaining sonorant. Where exactly this sound was inserted, if the sonorant remained and the quality of the sound depended on the environment. Syllabic nasals turned into *a when preceded by at least two consonants, while syllabic liquids ejected a prop vowel after them in the same environment. All remaining syllabic sonorants simply ejected a prop vowel before them:|-|It is likely the reflex of nasals before clusters started of as a nasalised neutral vowel, i.e. *ə̃, which later lost its nasalisation and neutralised differently than its oral equivalent, most importantly not engaging in the vowel colouring that would later take place.
column36: Whenever a laryngeal was surrounded by two true consonants - that is, all consonants excluding the semivowels *y *w - it ejected a prop vowel after itself:
column37:
Prop vowel colouring

The precise reflex of the recently created prop vowels heavily depended on their environment. First of all, it took up rounding from any previous consonant:
column39: Due to the regressive action of the boukolos rule, which delabialised labiovelars next to *u, this delabialised any labiovelar after which it occured:|-|It is worth noting that this did not affect new sequences of *wu, which stayed as is.
column40: The prop vowel took colour from surrounding laryngeals much like older *e:
column43:
Finally, any remaining prop vowels merged into *u when directly preceding *m, while all other prop vowels lost their distinctiveness by merging into *i:|-|As can be seen above, the treatment of syllabic sonorants and laryngeals in these contexts is particularly complicated, and the same can be said for the other western branches. The following comparison will remain superficial and simplified; as such, the reader is advised to read more specialised sources if they wish to learn more.

Syllabic sonorants interacting with adjacent laryngeals is a feature shared with Celtic, Greek and Latin, but not Germanic, which simply ignored the laryngeals and treated them the same way it treated lone syllabic sonorants. The later colouring of the prop vowel by adjacent laryngeals is only shared with Greek, however, and referred to as the so-called triple reflex. In other branches, the outcome tended to be an a-vocalism instead. Compare the following:

  • pie@(h₂)wĺ̥h₁neh₂|(h₂)wĺ̥h₁neh₂ > °WLANA°, pclt@w(u)lān-|w(u)lān-, grc@λῆνος|λῆνος=lênos, lat@lāna|lāna; compare to pgmc@wullō|wullō
  • pie@ǵr̥h₂nóm|ǵr̥h₂nóm > °GRANUMGRAIN°, pclt@grānom|grānom, lat@grānum|grānum; compare to pgmc@kurną|kurną; pie@pl̥h₂Kyéti|pl̥h₂Kyéti > °ISTRIKE°, grc@πλήσσω|πλήσσω=plḗssō
  • pie@ǵn̥h₃tós|ǵn̥h₃tós > °GNOTUSKNOWN°, pclt@gnātos|gnātos (through *gnōtos), grc@γνωτός|γνωτός=gnōtós, lat@nōtus|nōtus

The resulting vocalisations of syllabic sonorants and the position of the newly ejected vowel is particularly complicated in Carite, but significantly easier in the other branches. In Celtic, syllabic liquids preceded by a consonant and followed by a stop or *m ejected *i after them, while all other inconsonantal syllabic sonorants ejected *a before them. Latin liquids ejected *o before them, while the nasals ejected *e before them. The Greek development is considerably more complicated and readers are advised to consult §compgrammar§ and papers such as §greekrhv§ for an elaborate exposition. Germanic, as mentioned before, was very straightforward as it simply ejected *u before the syllabic sonorants. Some examples are included below:

  • pie@déḱm̥|déḱm̥ > °10°, pclt@dekam|dekam, grc@δέκα|δέκα=déka, lat@decem|decem, pgmc@tehun|tehun (with secondary *-n for *-m)
  • pie@mr̥tós|mr̥tós > °MORTUUSDEAD°, pclt@marwos|marwos, grc@βροτός|βροτός=brotós, lat@mortuus|mortuus, pgmc@murþą|murþą

In the same fashion Carite has some peculiar environment-dependent outcomes, so did the other branches. Papers such as §italiclaryngealsclhc§ may be consulted for more information.
column45:
Engels' Law

An unusual, but well-documented Carite change is the effect of laryngeals on consonants in word-initial position. They voiced plosives and sibilants, probably through a process of glottalisation:|-|
column50:
Similarly, semivowels underwent fortition with *y surfacing as *k and *w surfacing as *kʷ. Importantly, however, is that the fortition of *y only took place following *h₁ as opposed to the other consonants, which underwent this change regardless of the type of laryngeal:|-|A longstanding hypothesis is that the fortition of *h₁y resulted in *ḱ, which was still unmerged, but otherwise invisible to historical linguistics. This opinion is somewhat controversial, but unfalsifiable due to our inability to elucidate which exact allophone *y fortited to. The fact only *h₁ affected *y is in line with its word-initial treatment in Greek and can be explained through Byrd's improvement of Pinault's Law; this would imply *h₂ *h₃ would have been lost before *y before this phonological change could have taken place. For more information, please refer to §yod_and_hippos§.

This change is occasionally termed Engels' Law, and it was first posited by the Limburgish philologist Klaus Engels.
column52: It is likely that at this point the laryngeals lost differentiation and merged into one general laryngeal continuant, completing the second merger of laryngeals:
column53: The next loss of laryngeals (second laryngeal loss) happened to sequences of vowels with a laryngeal:|-|The lengthening of contracted laryngeal sequences still obeyed Osthoff's Law, shortening the new vowels when followed by a resonant and then an obstruent. Examples of this process are scant, but evident in the so-called conjunctive nominals, which, in early Carite, take special forms in subordinated clauses and in coordinated clauses; a typical example of this is the masculine noun °EKWOS°, its genitive plural attested both as the regular ekwōm and in the conjunctive form ekwomfe; the length of the vowel in the suffix is indicative of Osthoff's Law. With the deletion of the laryngeal and subsequent compensatory lengthening, any allophonous colouring effects were phonemicised. It is worth noting that Dybo's Law, which was responsible for pretonic shortening after the loss of laryngeals in Italo-Celtic and Germanic, did not affect Carite.
column55: After this, the laryngeals fail to effect any further changes, and are likely lost shortly thereafter, completing the third laryngeal loss:|-|This included all word-initial laryngeals immediately followed by a consonant, which were lost in all daughters except for Anatolian, Greek, Armenian and Phrygian. It is worth noting this change phonemicised what used to be allophones, i.e. the colouring of *e and Engels' Law.
column56:
Davide's Law

One of the longstanding issues in the evolution from Proto-Indo-European to Abean was the surfacing of some *e *ē as *a ā. The exact mechanism behind this shift is called Davide's Law and must have taken place following the dissolution of syllabic sonorants and laryngeals, but before the collapse of the three-way plosive system and (presumably) also before the fricativisation of the labiovelars. Davide's Law posits that pretonic *e *ē shift to *a ā when next to a rhotic, the semivowel *u or its vocalic equivalent *w, and any (labio)velar:
column60:
When preceding *n before another velar, the allophonic velarity of the nasal also triggered the same shift:|-|It is likely this change originally also affected the augment in roots starting with any of the consonants mentioned above, but we find no trace of this in inscriptions and it is likely it was analogised away later.

Due to the environment this change is conditioned by, several historical linguists have pointed out the noteworthy similarity to the phenomenon known as RUKI, which was long held to only affect satem languages. However, post-Proto-Germanic developments related to vowel lowering in RUKI-like environments have pointed towards the isogloss being shared with at least one centum language too (cf. §germanicruki§), so it is not unthinkable that the Carite shift may be explained in the same RTR vein.
column61: In a not yet fully explained context, some words show the effects of Davide's Law outside of these conditions. One of these conditions is after initial *s, which will be explained shortly after, but the others are more opaque. The effect again seems to be limited to pretonic *e *ē, although the range of adjacent consonants triggering it seems to be larger. Some Caritologists have suggested that dialectally, Davide's Law also affected any pretonic *e *ē next to voiced obstruents, citing the glottalic theory as a possible additional cause. Regardless, the conditions are not fully understood and we only posit the following:|-|Superficially, the fact Carite exhibits "too much" a-vocalisms is noteworthily similar to an identical problem in Latin. However, even though in both cases the new *a was originally *o, the conditions are entirely different. For more information on the Italic colouring of *o to *a, please refer to sources such as §latinmo§ and §ed_latin§.
column62:
Development of *h

Word-initial laryngeal voicing of *s enables the dating of another change, its word-initial, prevocalic debuccalisation:|-|Greek also took part in the debuccalisation of *s, although it was significantly more widespread, also taking place intervocalically and in some complex clusters. Compare the following:

  • pie@supnós|supnós > °HUPNOS°, pclt@sownos|sownos, grc@ὕπνος|ὕπνος=húpnos, lat@somnus|somnus, gmc@swefnaz|swefnaz
  • pie@sweḱrúh₂|sweḱrúh₂ > °SOCRUSAUNT°, pclt@swekrū|swekrū, grc@ἑκυρά|ἑκυρά=hekurá, lat@socrus|socrus, pgmc@swegrū|swegrū

It is worth noting that original *sw- retained the sibilant as is, even when the labial would later coalesce with the following vowel as demonstrated above.
column63:
Another concurrent change was the debuccalisation of word-initial prevocalic *gʰ:|-|It is probable that this change would also have affected word-initial *gʷʰ → *ɦʷ, but the labiovelarisation of its rounding probably reverted the change shortly thereafter, putting it at → *gʷʰ again. In Latin, we find <> for original *gʰ but in a far more widespread environment. Compare the following:

  • pie@ǵʰh₂éns|ǵʰh₂éns > °GANSGOOSE°, pclt@gansis|gansis, grc@χήν|χήν=khḗn, lat@ansēr|ansēr (through *hansēr), pgmc@gans|gans
  • pie@wéǵʰeti|wéǵʰeti > °VEHOBRING°, grc@ἔχω|ἔχω=ékhō, lat@vehō|vehō, pgmc@weganą|weganą
column64: In a handful of words, we find the effects of Davide's Law on words that etymologically started with *s. It is likely that the word-initial prevocalic merger of *s and *gʰ, where the latter triggered the change, resulted in these hypercorrections.
column65:
Dental assibilation

It is assumed that around this time, dental plosives following a velar plosive underwent assibilation, provided they were not followed by another consonant. This process affected regular velars and labiovelars alike:|-|This process was unique to Carite and can not be found in other western early Indo-European languages.
column69:
Aspiration loss

We can date the collapse of the three-way stop system to follow the dental assibilation. First up, we find a neutralisation between post-nasal voiced and aspirated plosives:|-|It was long assumed that an identical change occurred in Italic; however, recent evidence suggests that this must be a post-Italic development as Umbrian appears to lack it. As such, even though Latin has an identical development, we must consider these to be independent (cf. §soundchangeinitalic§).
column70:
After this post-nasal neutralisation, we can date the collapse of the three-way contrast system in plosives. The aspiration feature of voiced aspirates would combine with their voicing to produce a breathy phonation, which merged with voiceless tenues. A possible glottalic interpretation is that in these early Carite stages voicing was a creaky or glottalised feature (explaining laryngeal voicing of word-initial obstruents), and that breathy segments had more in common acoustically with voiceless tenues. Alternatively, we may posit that they simply devoiced first and only later lost their aspiration. Regardless, the internal history of this change is opaque, and we only posit:|-|Notably, this change did not affect word-initial *h derived from older *gʰ, as it had already merged with the reflex of initial *s, but did affect all internal instances of *gʰ—even those that were preserved as a result of prefixation. If Davide's Law did indeed sporadically include voiced stops in its environment, it is very likely that the collapse of the system postdates it. Likewise, the collapse precedes the assibilation described above as the cluster *gʰdʰ yielded *gz through *gʰz, not **ks through a hypothetical **kt.

The outcome of the original three-way contrast system in other languages is diverse. Compare the following cognates:

  • pie@h₃órbʰos|h₃órbʰos > °ORPHANOS°, pclt@orbos|orbos, grc@ὀρφανός|ὀρφανός=orphanós, lat@orbus|orbus, pgmc@arbaz|arbaz
  • pie@dʰuréh₂|dʰuréh₂ > °DOORTURA°, pclt@dworā|dworā, grc@θύρα|θύρα=thúra, lat@forum|forum (through *þorum), pgmc@durō|durō
  • pie@h₃méyǵʰeti|h₃méyǵʰeti > °MIIKOO° grc@ὀμείχω|ὀμείχω=omeíkhō, lat@meiō (through *meiχō), pgmc@mīganą|mīganą; pie@séǵʰos|séǵʰos > °SEGOSPOWER°, pclt@segos|segos, pgmc@segaz|segaz
  • pie@snígʷʰs|snígʷʰs > °SNIFI° (through *snikʷī), pclt@snigʷ(y)os|snigʷ(y)os, grc@νίφα|νίφα=nípha (through níkʷʰa), lat@nix (with oblique niv- through niɣʷ-), pgmc@snaiwaz|snaiwaz (through *snaigwaz)

The way Celtic handles the voiced aspirates is relatively straightforward, as it merged voiced aspirates into the regular voiced series. The only exception is *gʷʰ, which only deaspirated after *gʷ had shifted to *b. In Greek, the aspirates simply devoiced. It is likely that this is an isogloss shared with Carite before they later lost their aspiration in Carite. In Italic, we find word-initial devoicing of the aspirates, after which all aspirates became fricatives. In Latin times, these later shifted further - for exact details, one may consult §soundchangeinitalic§, although the examples listed above already give some clues. In Germanic, the voiced aspirates played a pivotal role in what is referred to as Grimm's Law. The three-way contrast system remained, although a chain shift took place that caused the fricativisation of voiceless stops, the devoicing of voiced stops and the deaspiration of aspirates. This can be conveniently conveyed as *Bʰ > B > P > F. For more information and examples, please consult §pie_to_pgmc§.

Besides the general fate of voiced aspirates in the numerous branches, it is worth noting that Carite, unlike Greek, did not undergo Grassman's Law. §grassmanchronology§ clearly shows Celtic and Germanic did not undergo dissimilatory deaspiration either, while his claims that Latin did are refuted by §latingrassman§.
column74:
Labiovelar developments

Long-distance assimilation of labial *p into a following *kʷ is assumed to have happened around this period. It is unknown if this change predated or postdated the collapse of the aspiration-based system, considering we find no suitable etymologies with original *bʰ and *gʷʰ. Examples are few but include the following:|-|While similar to the assimilation we may find in both Italic and Celtic, although individual developments, the Carite rule additionally requires the second labiovelar to be prevocalic. Compare the following:

  • pie@pénkʷe|pénkʷe > °5°, pclt@kʷenkʷe|kʷenkʷe, grc@πέντε|πέντε=pénte, lat@quīnque|quīnque, pgmc@fimfe|fimfe
  • pie@pokʷtéh₂|pokʷtéh₂ > °COCTUSSWEAT°; compare to pclt@kʷoxtos|kʷoxtos (through *kʷoktos), lat@coctus|coctus (through quoctus)

The development of the Germanic cognate seems like it fits the picture, but is actually an irregular assimilation the other way around, with *kʷ assimilating into the preceding *p with subsequent shifts to *f through Grimm's Law. On the preconsonantal delabialisation in the latter example, as well as the Carite outcome of *kʷs, see below. The Carite ordinal °5o° appears to defy the prevocalic requirement of the shift, but this is easily explained as analogy with the cardinal.
column75:
It was roughly at this time that the more lenis labiovelar plosives *kʷ *gʷ lost their velar plosion, but retained the lower frequency timbre of velarisation by labiodentalising instead of merely shifting to labials:|-|The development of labiovelars into labials (rather than labiodentals) may be observed in some of Carite's sister branches. Celtic, for example, merges *gʷ into *b with *gʷʰ taking its place. In Greek, labiovelars merged into labial or dental stops depending on their environment; the exact outcome also depends on the dialect. Latin retains *kʷ as <>, except for cases where it was later unrounded, while *gʷ merged into *w <> if not postnasal; some other Italic languages did shift them to labial plosives, however. Germanic retained the labialisation, although the series had been subject to Grimm's Law, yielding *hw *kw *gw. Compare the following cognates:

  • pie@linékʷti|linékʷti > °LEYKWOO° (through *linfṓ) > pclt@linkʷeti|linkʷeti, grc@λιμπάνω|λιμπάνω=limpánō, lat@linquō|linquō; pie@h₂ékʷeh₂|h₂ékʷeh₂ > °AQUAWATER°, lat@aquā|aquā, pgmc@ahwō|ahwō
  • pie@gʷih₃wós|gʷih₃wós > °VIVUS°, pclt@biwos|biwos, lat@vīvus|vīvus, pgmc@kwikwaz|kwikwaz; pie@h₁régʷos|h₁régʷos > °TWILIGHTDUSK°, grc@ἔρεβος|ἔρεβος=érebos, pgmc@rekwaz|rekwaz

The intervocalic labiovelar in pgmc@kwikwaz is a development unique to Germanic referred to as Cowgill's Law; for more information, please refer to §pie_to_pgmc§.

It is worth noting that Carite, unlike all other western centum languages - Celtic (before *y, *t, *s and *n), Greek (before *y), Latin (before all consonants) and Germanic (before *y, *r *t) - preserved labialisation in all cases with the obvious exception of the boukolos rule. Compare the words for "night":

  • pie@nókʷts|nókʷts > °NUFT° (through *nofsī), pclt@noxtV-|noxtV-, grc@νύξ|νύξ=núx (through nókʷts > núkts with Cowgill's Law), lat@nox|nox (through nocts), pgmc@nahts|nahts

Please do note that the conditions of delabialisation in the other branches mentioned above are simplifications. For further information, please consult the relevant sources.
column77:
Diphthong collapse

When any vowel was followed by *i *u, the sequence collapsed into a diphthong with *i *u surfacing as the semivowels *y *w. If they were formerly stressed, the stress shifted to the preceding vowel:|-|This widespread change primarily resolved hiatuses that originated from *VHV environments.
column79: Very early onwards, the homorganic vowel-sonorant sequences *eye coalesced into a long vowel:
column80: At some point between the coalescence of *eye and all further monophthongisations (as will be discussed below), semivowel dissimilation took place. More precisely, *w and *y shifted to *b and *l, respectively, when near or next to another instance of the same vowel or its vocalic equivalent. More precisely, *w shifted to *b before *u *ū and before a sequence of a vowel, optionally a resonant and *w, while *y shifted to *l before *i *ī and before a sequence of a vowel, optionally a resonant and *y:|-|We can confidently date this change to follow the coalescence of *eye, as the sequence *-eyey surfaces as *-ηῐ (*-ēj) and not **-ελη (*-elē). It is also worth noting that this dissimilation presumably did not take place if the vocalic equivalent preceded its semivowel equivalent; after all, we find °TREEKNOWER° rather than **δρυβῑστρις (**drubīstris).
column84: Sequences of a non-high vowel and a coda semivowel subsequently collapsed into a long vowel. In the case of *w, this also occurred when the non-high vowel followed it, provided that this *w did not directly follow a vowel and the vowel was not followed by a resonant and another consonant; in the case of the vowel restrictions, it is worth noting that these are the same conditions as Osthoff's Law.|-|Most importantly, the resulting opacity regarding the original Indo-European ablaut patterns led to the loss of productive ablaut.
column94:
Other minor changes

A few other consonant changes date to roughly this period, without an easy way to date them with precision relative to the rest of Abean developments of this time. For example, several clusters simplified word-initially:
column96: In a single occurrence, word-initial *sf- (from original *skʷ-) underwent fortition to *sp-:|-|As this appears to be the only case where said environment takes place, it is unknown if this was a regular change.
column97: Likewise, in a single occurence although without counterexamples, we find initial *dl- dissimilating to *gl-:|-|It is unknown if the same would happen to initial *tl- as Abean does not appear to continue any words with that initial cluster.
column98:
Word-initially, *m was fortited to *b before any liquid:|-|This change is shared with Greek, Latin and Germanic, while Celtic appears to lack it. Compare the following:

  • pie@mrégʰmn̥|mrégʰmn̥ > °BRAGNAZBRAIN°, grc@βρέχμα|βρέχμα=brékhma, pgmc@bragnaz|bragnaz
  • pie@mréǵʰus|mréǵʰus > °BRIGWIS°, grc@βραχύς|βραχύς=brakhús, lat@brevis|brevis
  • pie@ml̥h₂tis|ml̥h₂tis > pclt@mlātis|mlātis
column99: Curiously, prevocalic *fs and *ms both appear to surface as *sm:|-|It is likely the cluster *fs first dissimilated and merged into *ms before the metathesis occurred.
column101: Between two sonorants, sibilants appear to have been deleted:|-|While we do not have proof for the deletion of *z in this environment - if it occurred there at all - it is likely that it would have been deleted there as well.
column103: Word-finally, *d appeared to have rhotacised into *r, provided it was preceded by a vowel:|-|Alongside the evolution of *da- to Latin *la- (cf. §sabinel§), this change was originally used in defense of the implosive value [ɗ] of Proto-Indo-European *d. However, rhotacism is considerably more common than lambdacism and affects plain dentals alike. As such, its strength in this argument has diminished significantly and tends to no longer be included in such debates.
column104: Somewhere around this time, the short high vowels *i *u turned into glides when unstressed and preceding another vowel:|-|This does not appear to have taken place when following any cluster.
column106: Following the reduction of these unstressed high vowels, a minor palatalisation took place:|-|This assibilation of dentals resembles Greek, but is by no means as widespread as it is there. For the major palatalisation that affected nearly all Proto-Greek consonants, please refer to §compgrammar§.
column108: Stressed *ē *ō were raised in stressed syllables:
column112:
Nasal surface filter

A surface filter of nasal assimilation that applied across Carite history is also dated to have started up to this point in time:|-|It is worth noting that *m did not appear to assimilate into *n before *n, which was retained as the sequence *mn instead.
column115:
Carite Verner's Law

The change that is taken to define Carite as a fully independent language in its own ecosystem is the Carite Verner's Law, a structural parallel of Verner's Law in Germanic. Onsets of stressed, non-initial Carite syllables were voiced, and when the distinctive position of accent was lost to a word-initial accent relocation, the voicing phonemicised completely:|-|The voicing is likely to initially have affected only the onset of the stressed syllable that caused it, but voicing assimilation rules for clusters spread the voicing to the whole cluster. It is worth noting that, despite the name and similar effect - that is, the voicing of segments based on now-lost stress - this law significantly differed from its Germanic equivalent regardless. In Germanic, clusters were automatically disqualified from being affected by the law and the requirement was that the preceding syllable nucleus was unstressed. In Carite, clusters benefited significantly from the effects of this law and it only affected the onset of what was formerly a stressed syllable, as long as it was non-initial; as such, word-final coda voicing effects as in Germanic's *-az suffix (from *-os) are nowhere to be found in Carite.

While Carite and Germanic are the most well known examples of Indo-European branches losing phonemic stress or pitch accent only after it had functioned as the conditioning for other changes, these are by no means the only ones. Other stress-based Carite developments mentioned before are Davide's Law and the stressed raising of Proto-Indo-European *ē *ō. Outside of Carite, we find Dybo's Law - the pretonic shortening of vowels in some environments - which most certainly affected Celtic and quite possibly also Latin and Germanic; for more information, please refer to §dyboslaw§.
column120:
Minor consonant changes

Word-initial /w/, which only appeared before liquids or vowels, either fortited into /b/ or lenited into /h/, respectively:
column122: It is assumed that /s/ debuccalised word-finally when following a vowel at roughly the same time:
column123: Some posit a metathesis of an intervocalic NL sequence - however, due to the extreme limited distribution, it is possible this change was not systematic but just happened to affect all three retrievable examples:

Vowel developments

A short, unstressed vowel is deleted when directly preceding a long vowel.
column125: Intervocalic semivowels appeared to geminate in specific environments, triggering Osthoff's Law when relevant:|-|It is likely this change originally caused alterations due to vowels differing between suffixes. However, analogy must have occurred at some point after this, with the stem that underwent the gemination being generalised.
column127: Following the change above, it is likely that sequences of a vowel and a semivowel, at least preconsonantally or word-finally, started being considered a single diphthong. Some reconstruct an actual change, others find this distinction rather meaningless. Nonetheless, it is presented here:

column140: The same loss of nasals and accompanying lengthening and nasalisation occurred before another nasal, but only if the nasals were homoorganic:
column141: When preceding a rhotic, /s z/ most likely fronted around this time, yielding the slightly more dental allophones [θ ð]:

However, a separate change at roughly the same time provided another source of dental fricatives:|-|This change is rather controversial; this will be elaborated on further below.

It is not clear if new rhotics were deleted interconsonantally or if /z/ was deleted in the same environment before the change:|-|It is worth noting that before rhotics, /z/ was pronounced as [ð] and did not participate in the rhotacism, effectively phonemicising /ð/.

column148: An interaction between the labiodental fricatives and nasals took place with the fricatives either undergoing fortition into plosives postnasally or assimilating into a labial nasal prenasally:

column154: When unstressed /u/ or /i/ preceded their semivowel equivalents, they were deleted:

column157:
Lefèvre's Law

Interaction between dental plosives and liquids resulted in a chain shift which is, even today, not entirely well understood. Dental fricatives fortited into plosives before rhotics, which may have triggered a subsequent shift of old /tr/ and /dr/ to /tl/ and /dl/; in turn, old /tl/ and /dl/ dissimilated into /kl/ and /gl/. No counterexamples to these changes may be found. This chain shift is often referred to as Lefèvre's Law.
column163: The remaining dental fricative /θ/ only occurred word-finally after nasalised vowels, resulting from the old *-ns we saw before. For this reason, many believe that this fricative was never truly dental and had always been [s].
column165: Word-final /h/ was lost, triggering compensatory lengthening:
column167: /ps/ appears to dissimilate to /ks/:|-|While limited to two nominals, this change is particularly important in the formation of future stems of thematics and was morphologised. This change also notably phonemicises previous allophonic instances of [hs].
column168: Carite later underwent some form of liquid metathesis, more specifically in LV sequences, although this only occurred in specific conditions. First of all, the liquid must be preceded by a plosive. Secondly, the vowel needs to be short. Finally, the metathesis did not occur if the vowel was followed by a liquid or /h/ in the coda or if the sequence was word-final:
column170: Diphthongs where the first element was a long vowel were shortened:|-|This change evidently only occurred in word-final contexts, which was the only environment in which Osthoff's Law did not already cause this shortening.
column171: If they were ever distinct, the following diphthongs collapsed into long vowels:
column173: In word-initial contexts, when a plosive was followed by a nasal and a vowel, the vowel was nasalised and lengthened and the nasal underwent rhotacism:|-|Such an environment resulting into vowel lengthening is slightly unusual, to say the least. Nonetheless, we consistly find long vowels in lexemes that underwent this change. It is likely the lengthening is secondary and a result of analogy with other nasal vowels, which were consistently long in non-word-final environments (and even there, only polysyllables had short final nasal vowels). As such, it is possible this lengthening may only have taken place later than in Late Proto-Carite.
column174: Finally, some cluster simplification took place with plosives being deleted between sonorants and other plosives:
column179: While the exact dating is impossible, it is assumed that *ḫ started being pronounced in a uvular rather than a velar way around this period.
column180:
I-umlaut

A process similar to the Germanic i-umlaut and, as such, often referred to in a similar manner, took place. More specifically, the vowels *a *o *u, no matter their length, were fronted to *æ *ø *y when preceding a syllable with *j in its onset or *i *e as its nucleus. This also affected diphthongs where the second element was *i:|-|While this also significantly increased the occurrence of *ø *y, which were otherwise relatively marginal vowels, it also gave birth to [æ], a new allophone of *a in the aforementioned environments.
column183: In a sequence of two voiced plosives, the former assimilated into the latter:
column184:
A-umlaut

Not much later, a similar vowel harmony process took place, lowering *i *u if the next syllable contained *a:|-|The notation as *e₂ *o₂ is not utilised in all sources, but makes it clear that these lowered allophones were distinct from the older *e *o. It is easily provable that this process took place after i-umlaut, as the raised [æ] did not lower the high vowels.
column187: In a stressed syllable, onset *sp *st *sk undergoes debuccalisation which leads to the aspirated consonants *pʰ *tʰ *kʰ:
column190:
Intervocalic nasal-plosive clusters

When a sequence of a nasal and a voiced plosive was intervocalic, the nasal was lost, triggering nasalisation and compensatory lengthening on the preceding vowel:
column191: This set off a larger chain shift, where intervocalic sequences of a nasal and an unvoiced plosive underwent voicing:
column194: Finally, intervocalic sequences of an unvoiced plosive and a nasal underwent metathesis:
column197:
Vowel Harmony

A major change that would also cause lasting morphological effects was the widespread vowel harmony that occurred around the beginning of the second century. Only stressed vowels retained the full eight-vowel distinction, with unstressed vowels being limited to *a *i *u. This excluded diphthongs and *e₂ *o₂.|-|In fully unstressed particles, such as prepositions, there was no stressed vowel to use as reference. In these cases, every vowel was its own reference.
column199: Furthermore, *e₂ *o₂ merged into *e *o when stressed, but reverted to their previous *i *u in unstressed positions:
column202:
Carite Exon's Law

Similar to its equivalent in Latin, syncope took place in a medial sequence of two light syllables. Unlike Latin, however, which deleted the vowel in the former syllable, Old Carite underwent syncope in the latter syllable.
column203: In the earliest attestations, we already find <> for what used to be *ḫ. As we previously posited an uvular execution, it is likely it shifted to [ʁ] around this time, usually notated as <<ř>> in Caritology:

column221:
Stress changes

At some point in Old Carite history, stress shifted from being predictably word-initial to being predictably penultimate. Several changes, presumably taking place towards the end of Old Carite times, clearly show traces of such a stress system. For example, long, stressed word-initial vowels broke into a palatal glide and the original vowel:
column222: A short, unstressed, word-initial vowel was lost if the cluster that followed it formed a legal onset:|-|This change is particularly notable because it helps us determine that the voiced plosives *b *d *g presumably had lenited intervocalic allophones, which were subsequently phonemicised when these initial vowels were lost.

column224: When a short, unstressed vowel followed a plosive and preceded a prevocalic liquid, it was lost:

Rhotic behaviour

Up until this point, the language possessed two rhotics, i.e. /r ʁ/. Sometime prior to 450, this distinction faded, but only after several other changes had taken place. First of all, /ʁ/ was lost word-finally without inducing compensatory lengthening:

column397: §ed_greek§ reconstructs the Proto-Germanic etymon with *-ī- although §ed_germanic§ disagrees. While the *l~n alteration may date back to Proto-Indo-European times, it is more likely we are dealing with two separate derivations, a view which is supported by the difference in length. While the Germanic form may be traced back to the diminutive suffix *-ilaz, either Hoffmann's suffix *-hₓn- or the derivational *-ihₓnos may be identified in the Graeco-Armeno-Carite derivation. The presence of an o-grade in Armenian as well as its classification as an ea-stem points towards an independent Armenian derivation, while it is impossible to point out if the Graeco-Carite derivations, which are formally identical, are independent or areal innovations. While the association between hedgehogs and snakes appears to be common and a linguistic analysis of hedgehog as "snake-eater" checks out zoologically, an actual derivation only makes sense phonologically in Greek as its word for snake, grc@ἔχις=ékhis, would be the only pure reflex of a hypothetical pie@h₁éǵʰis, being displaced by pie@h₃égʷʰis in other branches. Any corruption of reflexes of the latter or of the lexeme for hedgehog in descendants must thus be secondary.

Reconstructions lead back to a root *katt- which, besides in Latin, is present identically in Proto-Celtic and Gaulish and, slightly further away, in Germanic. column397: The actual reconstruction of the root differs between authors, with the middle laryngeal being reconstructed both as *h₁ and *h₂. While this is irrelevant to the outcome in Carite, *h₂ seems more likely due to the Doric variant λᾶνος (lânos), if not a hyperdorism. More prevalent is the reconstruction with with an initial *h₂-. This laryngeal is reconstructed on the basis of the initial ḫ- in Hittite. §ed_celtic§ ascribes this to metathesis however, as neither Greek form shows any trace of the expected word-initial α-. While §ed_greek§ says the laryngeal might have been there originally, it must have vanished disappeared early in Greek history, possibly through dissimilation. The presence of the laryngeal would not affect the Carite outcome as Engels' law would require *h₂w- to be followed by a vowel. As pointed out by §ed_germanic§, the Germanic reflex requires a suffix-stressed form which slightly deviates from the others; however, §pie_to_pgmc§ departs from a radically stressed form instead.

column397: A word with a complicated etymology. The similarity of the first syllable to the Greek and Sanskrit forms is striking. However, the suffix of the Sanskrit form as well as the existence of san@वर्तक=vartaka points towards a later application of a productive Sanskrit suffix. The Greek suffixes tend to vascillate between γ/κ (g/k) which may point towards a Pre-Greek origin; however, this may just be a later analogical procedure. If a native word, grc@ὄρτυξ=órtux would be the expected result of *wórtogʷs where the voiced labiovelar would explain the voiced velar reflex (regularly delabialised through the boukólos rule after the application of Cowgill's law). column394: grc δόμος=dómos,lat domus,san दम=dáma,pslv dȏmъ,grc δῶ=dô,san दम्=dā́m,hye տուն=tun,pclt dāmos,pbsl domus
column397: The original root noun was clearly archaic and is only preserved in a handful of branches such as Greek. It was later reformed, occasionally as an u-stem but mostly as an o-stem with the later transfer to the fourth declension is because of the feminine gender. The generalisation of ն (n) in Armenian, which is the word-final reflex of *m, shows that the thematicisation took place after this generalisation had already spread throughout the paradigm. While at a first glance, Carite is isolated in reforming the word as an i-stem, the global remodelling of root nouns as i-stem explains this phenomenon. While u-stems also underwent this transfer, the expected result would have been *domwī. As such, we may convincingly state that Carite, like Armenian, preserved the root noun until the remodelling took place.

column397: A word with a problematic etymology. The first element is often compared to pie@séh₂l̥ ("salt"), whence °SALT° - however, this leaves the the *p unexplained. Given the presence of a *-d- extension in Armenian and Germano-Balto-Slavic, often as a u-stem, one may posit a pre-form **séh₂l̥dwih₂ with regular remodeling as i-stem. Unfortunately, this would result in Late Proto-Carite *halbi and the devoicing of the labial would be irregular. However, given the fact that the early Carite speakers presumably did not have access to the sea until not long before the Narbonne attestations and they only were familiar with sweetwater fishes, this word may be of substrate origin instead. Alternatively, this word may be a derivative of pie@selp- (whence °SELPOS°), with "(fish) oil" being generalised to "fish". However, the vocalism would be unexpected.

column397: A word with multiple suggested protoforms. While the first laryngeal is sometimes reconstructed as *h₁ or even *h₂, the consensus appears to be that the word-initial ο- (o-) of Greek appears to confirm the identity of *h₃. The majority seems to agree on *Hnéh₃- as a reconstruction - however, §oxf_intro§, §sketch_albanian§, §ed_celtic§ and §sketch_armenian§ reconstruct the root without a laryngeal and posit a single *o while §dic_gaulish§ simply reconstructs *nom-. The function of the second laryngeal appears to be to account for the discrepancy in terms of vowel length, as one may posit full grades and zero grades. One of the main arguments against the reconstruction of the second laryngeal appears to be the fact Tocharian retains a clear reflex of *ē. In order to account for this, §pie_to_pgmc reconstructs a third ablaut grade, being a lengthened e-grade, as this would prevent the laryngeal from colouring. §ed_greek§ suggests dissimilation of the second laryngeal to *h₁ instead. Either way, the lack of vowel length in Carite is clear. As **n̥h₃m- would likely have resulted in **nōm-, one could ask if the version with laryngeal is problematic for Carite. However, it is possible the preceding laryngeal prevented the lengthening - after all, there are no other comparable cases with word-initial *Hn̥HC.

column397: A word with a slightly problematic etymology. While the appurtenance of Greek and Sanskrit is very attractive, the Sanskrit form poses formal problems. For this reason, alternative etymologies are often posited, such as *wor(hₓ)dʰwo- for the Graeco-Aryan reflexes. However, there are no traces of a possible digamma in Mycenaean. If one would adhere to this theory, the only proof of *h₃ would expire, leading to many to reconstruct *h₂ instead, even though this is incompatible with the Carite reflex. *h₁, which is also sometimes reconstructed, is incompatible with the Germanic full grade. §ed_germanic§ posits an old compound of pie@h₃er- and pie@dʰeh₁-, although the loss of the second laryngeal would be puzzling. If the alternate etymology of Graeco-Aryan is applied to Carite, we would end up with an old **urdwos rather than *ordwos. However, considering the earliest attestation of this lexeme is a hapax legomenon, we may be dealing with a deviating form, and the merger of both options into *urdwos that followed makes it only more uncertain. No matter what the original etymology is, the Carite form seems to be closely linked to the Greek reflex.
